content: Today, you will see one very fresh game,
It was played during this weekend,
during the qualification tournament in Estonia, in last round.
wow, coco put her photo on forum!!
The tournament was played in Swiss system,
after 6 rounds, Tunnet had ensured 1st place,
having won 6 games in a row!
Now, the 7th match started, even Tunnet had brilliant score, he wanted to get perfect result,
so he played a real fight with Timo Ilu in last round.
In my opinion, it was very exciting.
Timo Ilu is a strong player,
he is also a member of Estonian national team
to represent Estonia in team WC.
In this game, Timo was black, Tunnet was white.
The opening was not surprising at all,
The evaluations of these two variants change in daily basis
just as someone discovers something new there,
the rates of the variant drop or increase
so, it is very important to be up-to-date with recent theories
Samsite used this 14th move against Aivo Oll,
whereas Tunnet preferred another 14th against Timo.
In past 2-3 months, 17-h7 has raised some excitement,
But now it has become quiet in that field,
I dont know exactly the final conclusion of this variant,
Does black have any interesting plan here?
i think it is white favour
Before we look further about Tunnet's game, lets check this variant for a moment.
meanwhile, let others warm up fingers :)

very hard to find decent black plan
so hard to find good black plan after 22
o10 is important control for white
one way is to use white fours
and here, it seems to go back to the old variant
That was a quick look at the h7,
but who knows, it might come back :))
guest, please use whisper to speak chinese to your friends
It seems this 18 is like a standard now.
Tunnet used this against Timo as well,
Which 20th moves do you know here?
indeed, two main styles are g6 and h4,
both have their advantages and disadvantages.
With Timo, Tunnet chose the passive 20th move.
Timo's 21st move was a bit surprise for me,
for some reason, I expected some more aggressive style,
by such move, he risks to give up one area completely, like happened in game,
therefore, lets think a moment here,
and let you all make a suggestion,
where would you play 21st move, if you were black??
Perhaps one general idea would be:
First neutralize the right wing, while trying to keep 9_13 alive,
and then play somewhere up left,
what do you think about it?
i think black should just try to spend right side material for defense
but maybe black can get some support for future development on left-upper
maybe white doesnt need to be too aggressive now
but main ideas at upper are same
to have chance to go e11 freely
so, as long as black can kill right side first
and make i11 appear not so dangerous
so, the key here is, black will struggle to kill right side,
and not let black easily change to left later
now black only has right wing
then, 22 basically kills black attack hope on left too
but still, it has some ideas in it too
black actually gives the burden of decision to whites,
when before black dictated the course of the game,
and white simply followed as best as possible,
then here, its hard to figure out for white,
to attack or defend, and where!
it was confusing moment for tunnet too, I believe
let tunnet tell us what was he thinking :)
tunnet, tell us how you finally chose h4
in aspects of attack, defense, space etc
his idea was to streghten upper side somehow with that stone
but yah, it gave away lower side
so for future, If I'd defend his movement at upper side I would feel comfortable at lower
like, one "sure area" for white guaranteed?
sometimes we must risk a bit,
and prepare for some heavy defense,
in order to make one solid area for self
because for top players, draw is not enough
so, they must work harder, to get win
I am sorry. I will behave.
can white be active now instead?
can black get VCT on left?
this makes the question even harder,
white has more than one tactics,
and to decide it, one should look deeper, into final outcome.
Perhaps tunnet decided, that white's activity would not be enough for immediate win, in fact, simply wasting white area,
while later still needs to defend blacks
so perhaps thats why Tunnet chose to defend first
for same purpose - to get win, not draw
Of course, defense was a risky decision.
As you can see from next moves,
It is not a happy moment in game.
The situation is now a bit out of white's control.
But Tunnet found an excellent way to defend it!
Timo has not much choice here either,
all moves forced for both sides.
and now, white can save the game with one move - where??
maybe if 45 and 47 not so soon, then black can have three with k11, L10?
therefore, maybe its a good homework question
the move that Tunnet used was very safe.
And by then it was clear, white will win this game,
it was only a matter of time.

time trouble was pushing the players too.
63-d7 would have hold for a while
Tunnet is playing so well even under short time.
I could not watch this game till the end,
I left the room at move 35,
but I already understood by then,
that Timo will fail this game, because of great f14 defense.
Later at home, I began to analyse this,
And many interesting questions came to my mind.
after this, I could not find win
So, finally, I still dont know the answer.
For ending of this class, one tiny puzzle, for beginners
who can show me black win here?
so you can have relaxing week
since you are in tournament too
it was nice to be here, see you all next week!
